00:07:31.190 --> 00:07:34.740
Our topic is the relationship
between faith and imagination.

00:07:34.740 --> 00:07:37.380 position:56%
I'm really not aware of the more
compelling instance of that relation

00:07:37.380 --> 00:07:40.870
in modern fiction in the way
Marilynne Robinson reimagines the

00:07:40.870 --> 00:07:46.190 position:56%
Christian, and more specifically the
Calvinist conception of divine grace

00:07:46.190 --> 00:07:49.070
in the three novels
of her Gilead trilogy.

00:07:49.070 --> 00:07:51.800
Those are Gilead, Home,
and Lila, of course.

00:07:51.800 --> 00:07:56.350
She does so impart the remarkable
elaboration and transposition

00:07:56.350 --> 00:08:00.090
of the most famous imaginative
depiction of divine grace

00:08:00.090 --> 00:08:02.040
in the New Testament,
the so-called Parable

00:08:02.040 --> 00:08:05.100
of the Prodigal Son
in the Gospel of Luke.

00:08:05.100 --> 00:08:07.800
A man has two sons,
and the younger asked

00:08:07.800 --> 00:08:09.990
for his inheritance in advance.

00:08:09.990 --> 00:08:11.290
The father grants the request.

00:08:11.290 --> 00:08:15.020
The son goes off, squanders his
patrimony through dissonant living,

00:08:15.020 --> 00:08:19.190
and returns home impoverished
and disgraced.

00:08:19.190 --> 00:08:20.650
His father not only forgives him,

00:08:20.650 --> 00:08:23.820
but amazingly throws
a party in his honor.

00:08:23.820 --> 00:08:26.670
The older son, who was always
been dutiful and obedient,

00:08:26.670 --> 00:08:28.670
objects to this special treatment,

00:08:28.670 --> 00:08:31.700
but the father gently
rebukes him explaining that,

00:08:31.700 --> 00:08:35.010
"This brother of yours was
dead, and has come to life.

00:08:35.010 --> 00:08:36.920
He was lost and has been found."

00:08:36.920 --> 00:08:39.260
I think I could show how echoes

00:08:39.260 --> 00:08:42.280
of this parable pervade
Robinson's trilogy,

00:08:42.280 --> 00:08:46.000
but it's most obviously evoked
by the middle novel, Home.

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:50.200
Home begins with a child's return
to a father, only this child,

00:08:50.200 --> 00:08:53.530
named Glory, is a younger
sister, not a brother.

00:08:53.530 --> 00:08:57.330
Her only sin was misplaced trust
in a fiancÃ© who jilted her.

00:08:57.330 --> 00:08:59.840
She isn't greeted by
any sort of party,

00:08:59.840 --> 00:09:03.900
and she quickly assumes the role of
the dutiful and obedient caregiver

00:09:03.900 --> 00:09:08.100
of her ailing father, Presbyterian
Minister Robert Boughton.

00:09:08.100 --> 00:09:10.810
The real prodigal son,
her elder brother,

00:09:10.810 --> 00:09:13.160
Jack, soon comes home as well.

00:09:13.160 --> 00:09:15.060
Much of the novel focuses
on his difficult

00:09:15.060 --> 00:09:19.130
and never-quite-finished
reconciliation with their father.

00:09:19.130 --> 00:09:21.670
Jack, who remains the
father's favorite,

00:09:21.670 --> 00:09:24.710
despite his delinquent childhood
and his many years of absence

00:09:24.710 --> 00:09:29.240
from the family home, eventually
leaves before disclosing the act

00:09:29.240 --> 00:09:32.200
that would have been his
greatest sin in his father's eyes,

00:09:32.200 --> 00:09:35.500
but is also the source of
his own moral redemption,

00:09:35.500 --> 00:09:37.260
his marriage to an
African American woman

00:09:37.260 --> 00:09:40.450
and his fathering of
a mixed-race son.

00:09:40.450 --> 00:09:41.880 position:56%
Jack's wife, Della, and son, Robert,

00:09:41.880 --> 00:09:45.070
show up at the family home
just after Jack has left.

00:09:45.070 --> 00:09:48.560
So, Glory, not the father,
finds out the truth.

00:09:48.560 --> 00:09:51.030
The novel ends with
Glory prophesying

00:09:51.030 --> 00:09:54.960
in her own imagination the
day when Jack's son, Robert,

00:09:54.960 --> 00:09:58.980
will return to the homestead truly
answering his father's prayers

00:09:58.980 --> 00:10:03.140
in a way that Jack never quite
answered his own father's prayers.

00:10:03.140 --> 00:10:06.980
And that, Glory sees
as the long delayed

00:10:06.980 --> 00:10:10.690
but infinitely merciful
expression of God's grace.

00:10:10.690 --> 00:10:14.370 position:56%
Now that only scratches the surface
of Robinson's treatment of the theme

00:10:14.370 --> 00:10:18.330
of grace, explicitly analyzed by
the terminally ill protagonist

00:10:18.330 --> 00:10:22.110
and narrator of the first
novel, Reverend John Ames,

00:10:22.110 --> 00:10:24.920
and reworked in an entirely
new way through the thoughts

00:10:24.920 --> 00:10:29.560 position:56%
of his religiously uneducated and
much younger wife, Lila, protagonist

00:10:29.560 --> 00:10:32.100
and namesake of the third novel.

00:10:32.100 --> 00:10:35.400
What gives Robinson's exploration
of grace, its imaginative depth,

00:10:35.400 --> 00:10:38.810 position:56%
is not just the variety of personal
angles from which she approaches it,

00:10:38.810 --> 00:10:42.780
but the subtle way in which she
connects those personal stories

00:10:42.780 --> 00:10:48.050 position:56%
with the salient movements and
events that inform or surround them.

00:10:48.050 --> 00:10:52.100
Abolitionism, the Civil War, the
Dust Bowl, the Great Depression,

00:10:52.100 --> 00:10:54.960
the beginning of the
Civil Rights Movement.

00:10:54.960 --> 00:10:56.450
Throughout the trilogy,
these elements

00:10:56.450 --> 00:11:00.500
of history sometimes lie dormant,
sometimes hunt the present,

00:11:00.500 --> 00:11:05.440
sometimes break violently through
the surface of her narrative.

00:11:05.440 --> 00:11:07.430
I'd like to start our discussion.

00:11:07.430 --> 00:11:10.660
I think I'll start with
you, Geraldine Brooks.

00:11:10.660 --> 00:11:13.230
Again, our topic is fiction,
faith, and imagination.

00:11:13.230 --> 00:11:16.290
As I just suggested, one
of the fascinating elements

00:11:16.290 --> 00:11:20.010 position:56%
of Robinson's fiction is the way she
weaves together religious concerns

00:11:20.010 --> 00:11:22.990
with a rich, historical context.

00:11:22.990 --> 00:11:26.410
What's your sense of the way
that works in her novels?

00:11:27.620 --> 00:11:33.030
&gt;&gt; GERALDINE BROOKS: Marilynne
Robinson's novels temporarily are

00:11:33.030 --> 00:11:36.980
situated in the near past.

00:11:36.980 --> 00:11:42.090
It's not traditionally what would
be described as historical fiction.

00:11:42.090 --> 00:11:49.250 position:56%
It's in what I'd like to think of
as Henry James' designated safe zone

00:11:49.250 --> 00:11:54.290
because James famously once
observed that any attempt to write

00:11:54.290 --> 00:12:00.070 position:56%
about a period more than 50 years
removed from one's zone is worthless

00:12:00.070 --> 00:12:03.310
and should not be attempted

00:12:03.310 --> 00:12:10.370
because the old consciousness
will be too elusive to us.

00:12:10.370 --> 00:12:15.970
Actually, if you think about it,
if you're a novelist in the middle

00:12:15.970 --> 00:12:22.530 position:56%
of the journey of your life, that
50-year window added to the 50 years

00:12:22.530 --> 00:12:27.370
of your own experience gives
you an entire century in which

00:12:27.370 --> 00:12:32.950
to apply your trade, which is a
not ungenerous period of time.

00:12:32.950 --> 00:12:37.530
And I think in the case of
Marilynne's luminous novels,

00:12:37.530 --> 00:12:46.330 position:56%
this is very important because I
can't imagine Gilead set after 1960.

00:12:46.330 --> 00:12:53.260
I think it is much better set in
the slightly more distant past.

00:12:53.260 --> 00:12:56.680
Perhaps, if you wanted to
look for a dividing line,

00:12:56.680 --> 00:13:00.720
it would be before you could
possibly have a Time Magazine cover

00:13:00.720 --> 00:13:04.020
that said, "Is God Dead?"

00:13:04.020 --> 00:13:10.250
I think you're in a time period
where the corrosive influence

00:13:10.250 --> 00:13:16.440
of materialistic skepticism has not
yet eroded the social fabric of,

00:13:16.440 --> 00:13:20.070
at least, the English-speaking
world to the extent

00:13:20.070 --> 00:13:23.520
that happened perhaps
after the '60s.

00:13:23.520 --> 00:13:33.030
It reminds me of a wonderful essay
by James Wood in his collection

00:13:33.030 --> 00:13:40.280
of The Broken Estate where he talks
about how the novel itself was,

00:13:40.280 --> 00:13:50.620
in a way, corrosive to faith
because the novel is an as-if form.

00:13:50.620 --> 00:13:56.730
You're creating as if, but
you're not creating certainty.

00:13:56.730 --> 00:14:02.430
And he talks about the very few
brilliant writers who are able

00:14:02.430 --> 00:14:08.380
to retain a mysticism and a
religious element in their fiction

00:14:08.380 --> 00:14:10.960
with the true belief
in fiction itself

00:14:10.960 --> 00:14:13.160
and the prophecies of fiction.

00:14:13.160 --> 00:14:18.060
He singles out Virginia Woolf and
talks about the gentle dalliance

00:14:18.060 --> 00:14:21.330
that she has between
religion and mysticism.

00:14:21.330 --> 00:14:25.780
And I think that Marilynne Robinson
is not a gentle dalliance at all.

00:14:25.780 --> 00:14:29.410
It is a passionate,
sweaty, congress.

00:14:30.430 --> 00:14:38.280
I think it works very beautifully
because she sees the mystical

00:14:38.280 --> 00:14:41.180
and religious in the ordinary.

00:14:41.180 --> 00:14:44.510
It doesn't have to be a
virgin birth to be wonderful

00:14:44.510 --> 00:14:50.070
because any birth is a miracle
as Ames' love for his young son,

00:14:50.070 --> 00:14:53.260 position:56%
so beautifully evoked, demonstrates.

00:14:53.260 --> 00:14:58.250
Then, I think of that wonderful
passage that Ames reflects

00:14:58.250 --> 00:15:00.350
that light is constant and
we just turn over in it.

00:15:00.350 --> 00:15:01.650
Every day is one day.

00:15:01.650 --> 00:15:02.950
Once you have that
thought, then who needs

00:15:02.950 --> 00:15:04.250
to argue whether the world
was created in six days?

00:15:04.250 --> 00:15:05.550
It becomes a magnificent
irrelevancy.

00:15:05.550 --> 00:15:06.850
You can have the faith without.

00:15:06.850 --> 00:15:08.150
&gt;&gt; STEVEN KNAPP: Thanks very much.

00:15:08.150 --> 00:15:09.450
Thank you.

00:15:09.450 --> 00:15:12.710
Alan, you're, among
