you've noticed how in recent years,

00:15:45.280 --> 00:15:47.260
science has been highly
critical of religion,

00:15:47.260 --> 00:15:49.440
and tend to affirm
evidence-based reasoning

00:15:49.440 --> 00:15:51.480
and contrast to reliance on faith.

00:15:51.480 --> 00:15:53.450
Defenders of religion
often respond by arguing

00:15:53.450 --> 00:15:57.130
that science itself relies
on its own kind of faith.

00:15:57.130 --> 00:15:58.430
What's your take on that?

00:15:58.430 --> 00:15:59.900
Does faith play a role in science?

00:15:59.900 --> 00:16:01.810
If so, what kind of faith?

00:16:01.810 --> 00:16:03.820
How do you think about
that in relation

00:16:03.820 --> 00:16:07.720
to your imaginative engagement
with both religion and science?

00:16:09.120 --> 00:16:12.380
&gt;&gt; ALAN LIGHTMAN: I think,
for me, faith is belief

00:16:12.380 --> 00:16:16.470
in something that you can't prove.

00:16:16.470 --> 00:16:22.980 position:56%
The folklore is that everything
that science believes, it can prove,

00:16:22.980 --> 00:16:29.550
and nothing that religion
believes, it can prove.

00:16:29.550 --> 00:16:38.840
I think that science and religion
have very different methods

00:16:38.840 --> 00:16:46.700
of arriving at their beliefs, but
I think there is a faith in both.

00:16:46.700 --> 00:16:53.180
The faith in science is something
that's very, very fundamental,

00:16:53.180 --> 00:16:57.530
the kind of faith that
scientists have.

00:16:57.530 --> 00:17:03.590
It's something that one might call
the central doctrine of science.

00:17:03.590 --> 00:17:08.050
And the central doctrine
of science is

00:17:08.050 --> 00:17:13.430
that the universe is
lawful and logical.

00:17:13.430 --> 00:17:23.340
It's a doctrine that we scientists,
learn as graduate students.

00:17:23.340 --> 00:17:28.620
We may not learn it
consciously but it's in the air.

00:17:28.620 --> 00:17:33.140
It's a belief that just
osmosis into the skin.

00:17:33.140 --> 00:17:39.180
It's a fundamental working
belief that scientists have.

00:17:39.180 --> 00:17:42.290
It's a belief that can't be proved.

00:17:42.290 --> 00:17:49.500
It has to be taken on faith because
no matter how much science knows

00:17:49.500 --> 00:17:56.230
and no matter how successful our
theories are, they're incomplete.

00:17:56.230 --> 00:18:02.010 position:56%
There are things that we don't know,
which Marilynne has talked about,

00:18:02.010 --> 00:18:03.640
things that science doesn't know.

00:18:03.640 --> 00:18:08.230
We can't be certain that all parts

00:18:08.230 --> 00:18:12.040
of the universe are
lawful and logical.

00:18:12.040 --> 00:18:17.350
We don't know for sure whether some
new phenomena discovered tomorrow

00:18:17.350 --> 00:18:19.070
will be lawful and logical.

00:18:19.070 --> 00:18:20.370
We can't be certain.

00:18:20.370 --> 00:18:26.070
The belief in the central
doctrine that everything

00:18:26.070 --> 00:18:32.540
in the physical universe is lawful
and logical, that is something

00:18:32.540 --> 00:18:34.830
that has to be taken on faith.

00:18:34.830 --> 00:18:38.790
&gt;&gt; STEVEN KNAPP: You've also
expressed the interest of times

00:18:38.790 --> 00:18:42.960
in relation between physical and
nonphysical conceptions of reality.

00:18:42.960 --> 00:18:45.490
Can you say maybe a little bit
more about that as a physicist,

00:18:45.490 --> 00:18:48.070
and how you think about
the nonphysical?

00:18:48.070 --> 00:18:54.400
&gt;&gt; ALAN LIGHTMAN: Marilynne
has written wonderfully

00:18:54.400 --> 00:19:01.140
about science and religion.

00:19:01.140 --> 00:19:10.650
She suggests in her writing
that we make too much a deal

00:19:10.650 --> 00:19:14.280
out of the difference between
the physical and nonphysical,

00:19:14.280 --> 00:19:17.450
but we make too big a distinction.

00:19:17.450 --> 00:19:22.460
What she says, and please
correct me, Marilynne,

00:19:22.460 --> 00:19:25.750
if I'm getting you wrong.

00:19:25.750 --> 00:19:31.000
She says that because
the knowledge of science

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:35.600
about the physical
universe is incomplete

00:19:35.600 --> 00:19:42.400
that we can't confidently
make an opposition

00:19:42.400 --> 00:19:45.660
between the physical universe
and a nonphysical universe

00:19:45.660 --> 00:19:49.880
because we don't really fully
understand the physical universe.

00:19:49.880 --> 00:19:54.990
I agree with part of
that, but not all of it.

00:19:54.990 --> 00:19:57.750
I do agree that the
knowledge of science

00:19:57.750 --> 00:20:00.450
about the physical
universe is incomplete.

00:20:00.450 --> 00:20:09.450
For me, as both a scientist, and
a humanist, and if I can say,

00:20:09.450 --> 00:20:13.680
a spiritual person, I think the
distinction between the physical

00:20:13.680 --> 00:20:19.260
and the nonphysical
universe is very important.

00:20:19.260 --> 00:20:26.150
I think that there are
experiences that we have

00:20:26.150 --> 00:20:29.270
and probably everybody
here has had them,

00:20:29.270 --> 00:20:32.590
you could call them
transcendent experiences,

00:20:32.590 --> 00:20:37.450
that science will never be able
to explain even in principle,

00:20:37.450 --> 00:20:40.850
will never be able
to fully comprehend.

00:20:40.850 --> 00:20:47.550
You can hook a hundred billion
electrodes to my neurons

00:20:47.550 --> 00:20:53.330
and measure every electrical
output of each neuron,

00:20:53.330 --> 00:20:58.080
but that will not explain the
experience that I have in looking

00:20:58.080 --> 00:21:01.190 position:56%
at the stars at night or the feeling

00:21:01.190 --> 00:21:04.580
that there's something
larger than myself.

00:21:04.580 --> 00:21:10.960
That, for me, is part of
the nonphysical universe.

00:21:10.960 --> 00:21:21.730
If we believe in God, if God
exists, every religion that I know

00:21:21.730 --> 00:21:28.200 position:56%
of has a conception of God in which
God does not live in time and space.

00:21:28.200 --> 00:21:32.700
God is not subject
to laws and rules.

00:21:32.700 --> 00:21:34.870
And so God would also be a part

00:21:34.870 --> 00:21:38.660
of what I would call the
nonphysical universe.

00:21:38.660 --> 00:21:43.860
On the other hand, I am a strong
subscriber to the central doctrine

00:21:43.860 --> 00:21:46.580
of science having said all of that.

00:21:46.580 --> 00:21:51.700
And I do think that there
is a vast range of phenomena

00:21:51.700 --> 00:21:56.900 position:56%
that science does understand, that
science can explain, that is subject

00:21:56.900 --> 00:22:02.520
to the laws that we understand, and
I call that the physical universe.

00:22:02.520 --> 00:22:07.660
So, I need to have a distinction
between those two universes

00:22:07.660 --> 00:22:13.560
to live a life both as a
scientist and as a humanist.

00:22:13.560 --> 00:22:14.860
