00:33:52.810 --> 00:33:57.820
To me, that's very
close to the imagination

00:33:57.820 --> 00:34:06.160
because in the imagination, we
are creating things in our minds

00:34:06.160 --> 00:34:15.550
that may not be concrete, that
may not be visible; and yet,

00:34:15.550 --> 00:34:27.650
they are ideas that motivate us,
that provoke us, that stimulate us.

00:34:27.650 --> 00:34:37.780
And so that's a connection that
I see at a really low level

00:34:37.780 --> 00:34:40.870
between faith and imagination.

00:34:43.210 --> 00:34:46.180
&gt;&gt; PAUL HARDING: I think
the act of creating art,

00:34:46.180 --> 00:34:50.260
and the act of cultivating your
imagination, the discipline

00:34:50.260 --> 00:34:54.510
of observation, and the discipline
of being able to observe things

00:34:54.510 --> 00:35:00.140
as intensely and as closely
as possible, and render them

00:35:00.140 --> 00:35:03.240
on to the pages aesthetically,
to put aesthetic pressure on them

00:35:03.240 --> 00:35:08.010
in the case of writing
fiction is an act of devotion.

00:35:08.010 --> 00:35:09.320
It's an act of obedience.

00:35:09.320 --> 00:35:11.140
It's an act of prayer.

00:35:11.140 --> 00:35:16.690 position:56%
With that beautiful kind of
commerce between, it's in your mind.

00:35:16.690 --> 00:35:21.230
There's this onto-epistemological
state

00:35:21.230 --> 00:35:25.850
where your mind is generating these
aesthetic productions and working

00:35:25.850 --> 00:35:27.860
with metaphors that are so bound.

00:35:27.860 --> 00:35:29.160
They build up.

00:35:29.160 --> 00:35:30.460
Then, they topple.

00:35:30.460 --> 00:35:31.760
You build them up again.

00:35:31.760 --> 00:35:35.960
But, then, you end up with this
book that goes out into the world.

00:35:35.960 --> 00:35:39.980
